>>35828068
So here's my numbers, using my own typesetting as a guide.
If you go with a 6" * 9" softcover trade paperback, you're looking at 250 to 290 pages, plus about 5-10 for frontmatter/backmatter.

Here's the breakdowns for 295 pages total:
At 11 USD, you have a printing cost of 4.39 (this comes out of your 70% royalties!), so the absolute minimum sale price (and yours for author copies) is 7.32. You make 2.21 per copy for normal distribution, and 0.02 for expanded distro.
Mind that I'm calculating pages on the same margins/font size as a professional hardcover/trade PB, not using Amazon's really fucked up templates. Do not use them.

ebooks is another price break. You have a max price of 9.99 for the 70% royalties (and must also be at least 20% less than the physical copy).
I don't have a formula for the ebook price/royalties that figures the end result, and since that's based on megabyes instead of page count I can't give you a good answer.
But I'm assuming that you can easily make the same end royalty off an ebook sale as physical. After all, any self-publishing outlet will tell you the majority of overall sales are ebook.
And please, do your research and check the file on multiple platforms before making it live. Just like a physical version, you're going to be spending time getting proof copies and checking that against your final typesetting.

What I can say:
Mine should look as professional inside as a published book (I shall not rant about Amazon's retarded templates and their unreadable kerning...), be about 360-370 pages, about 160k words, and cost ~ 15.00 USD
I just need a damned cover.

That one asshole who still refuses to use a tablet here. I think the best inspirations come from personal experience, that way you can draw from the feelings that you know personally, things you've watched, the people and experiences that they've told you about. Explore history and media of the specific time period that you look to for your background. Details make a massive difference in the personality of a character, take Lemmy Kilmister of motorhead. A Long haired badass motherfucker of a mountain of rock. He wore jackboots, denim and some spicy german type paraphernalia, he didn't give any shit that wasn't given naturally. The man grew to be the speedfreak of ledgends. How? He'd been through a lot, he had a gay roommate get murdered, he hung out with hendrix, Wendy O williams was in his social circle. I've went on a complete tangent on character development but whatever, it makes a lot of difference in the psychology of a character that differentiates them from some donut steel

>Lemmy Kilmister
Since you brought him up, I think one of the keys to characters is what kind of compassion they have.
Lemmy grew up in an age where reading and intellect were supposedly valued. Yet through his experiences as a roadie (the knives Keith Emerson used to stick in his Moogs to hold down notes were Lemmy's nazi loot! (and just the thought of Lemmy hanging with both ELP as a roadie and Hawkwind as a bassist)) he came into a do-it-for-myself style. It made him even more of an outcast from society. The guy had a front row seat to the late 60s, was surrounded by the underground zeitgeist of Moorcock's New Worlds, and more.
What did it get him? Pain & sorrow. He watched friends and lovers die. He knew it would eventually come for him. But those that were still there, he valued. With what time you are granted, live it.
If you listen to the parallels between Lemmy and some of the old men of American country...there's not much difference except volume. They don't need others to shower them with empty praise. They might not want a large social circle. But dig deep and there's a pearl of compassion that kills them as certainly as the drugs.
Don't stop and assign a flaw just to round out the character; find your their nacre.
